answers.body_markdown:
If you expect your query to return the number of duplicates then no it is not correct.&lt;br/&gt;
The condition `t1.id &lt; t2.id` will join every `id` of `t1` with all `id`s from `t2` that are greater resulting on more rows or less rows (in the case of only 2 duplicates) and rarely in the expected number.&lt;br/&gt;
See the [demo][1].&lt;br/&gt;
If you want to see all the duplicates:

    select * from consignment t
    where t.service = &#39;CLRC&#39; 
    and exists (
      select 1 from consignment
      where service = t.service and id &lt;&gt; t.id and hawb = t.hawb 
    )  

See the [demo][2].&lt;br/&gt;
If you want to delete the duplicates and keep only the one ones with the max `id` for each `hawb` then:

    delete from consignment
    where service=&#39;CLRC&#39;
    and id not in (
      select id from (
        select max(id) id from consignment
        where service=&#39;CLRC&#39; 
        group by hawb
      ) t  
    );
See the [demo][3].&lt;br/&gt;


  [1]: https://www.db-fiddle.com/f/d3mhr5ANuZgH74Q9zc4gwh/1
  [2]: https://www.db-fiddle.com/f/d3mhr5ANuZgH74Q9zc4gwh/6
  [3]: https://www.db-fiddle.com/f/d3mhr5ANuZgH74Q9zc4gwh/5

